title: For Trade:  Stolen Guns Page on Facebook
postcontent:
I just started this Facebook page.

I have looked around and couldn't find a decent page for reporting stolen guns to the gun community at large. It's my opinion that gun owners see a lot more in person w/ no idea where they came from & no paper trail. It's pretty much the only way to sell a stolen gun. I see it as our duty to our fellow gun owners to help keep an eye out for each other & help where we can. 

So, please join the group, post what gun/model serial number and any other relevant info there may be (Contact info, LEO Dept and the like.Everyone please share on your walls and groups nation wide. title: For Sale:  Colt Python 6" From Colt's Custom Shop - NIB- From 1978
postcontent:
I purchased this Python from the long defunct JPL Guns in Lawrence, Kansas in 1985. It came out of Colt's Custom Shop in 1978 and was in JPL's glass case marked "Personally Owned Firearm - Not For Sale." That sticker is still affixed to the well-worn original Colt Box. Of course, since it was marked not for sale I had to try to buy it. It took the trade of two other fine handguns and a cash hand of poker to walk out the door with it. I will be glad to provide a sworn letter to the buyer if desired. It has sat in my safe now for 28 years. In that span of time I've owned a total of four different Pythons, a couple of Trooper Mk IIIs and a couple of Detective Specials, and as fine a revolvers as they all are, none come close to the action on this one. And no matter what angle or lighting is used, the camera simply cannot capture the incredible deep beauty that was Colt's Royal Blue at that time. There are many more pictures available; just email for them.

I'm old now, and I am simply not ever going to take this gun out and shoot it. I suppose there are still some fine unfired Pythons out there, but probably few like this one. How to say this in the most polite possible way: I'll be using the funds to enhance my granddaughter's college account, so please don't waste my time and yours with low ball offers or trades, I am not interested and they will be ignored. I figure I will probably need to list this revolver on Gunbroker to get its value but I decided to try Armslist locally first. If you're looking at Armslist from outside Colorado, yes, I will ship this gun from my dealer to yours at extra cost. Thanks for taking the time to read this listing.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Kimber SIS Pro  LIKE NEW IN BOX !
postcontent:
It is getting hard to find a Kimber SIS for sale these days. This is a nice one: all original and beautiful.  It has the original  premier quality 8-rnd Kimber ProTac stainless steel magazine.  It has been shot a few times, but there are no scuffs, scratches or handling marks.  This gun looks brand new.

The Special Investigative Section of the Los Angeles Police Department asked Kimber to build them a gun with Kimber's standard build including match barrel, match trigger, wide grip safety, beveled mag well and checkered flat backstrap, and then to add the following extra features:  stainless steel slide and frame, special shaped tritium night sights with square edge for one-handed cocking, flat milled top of slide to cut down on sight glare, ambidextrous safety, checkered front strap for more sure grip, SIS light weight hammer, and the series 70 style firing system (no firing pin safety).  Kimber coated it with their KimPro coating, gave it a nice set of custom wood grips and a stylized SIS milled into the slide instead of cocking serrations.  It was so popular that Kimber made an extended production run for the civilian market for about five years.  Production of the SIS version was discontinued in Jan 2010. 

As the special build configuration for the most elite group of the largest city police force in the world, these have become a bit of a collectible.  When available, this gun sold for $1725 at Osage County Guns, a Kimber master dealer. To enjoy the same features on a new gun, you'd have to step up to Kimber's Super Carry Pro HD, another $1700 gun, if you can get it.

The Pro (4 inch) size is perfect for serious shooting and great for concealed carry.

Response to questions:
If you're reading this, THE GUN IS AVAILABLE.  No registration, taxes or shipping.  I'd like a face to face sale in Tulsa or Rogers County.  If you're in another state, thanks for your interest, but I'm not shipping this gun now.  If it doesn't sell this month, it may be listed in September on Gunbroker.com, and I will take the necessary steps to ship the gun.

This is the SIS PRO (series 70 style fire control system) not the politically correct PRO II (series 80 style).  It is NOT approved by the California state government.  Sorry.

I will trade this gun and $200 for one ounce of gold. 

Yes, my timeline for settlement on this gun is very short, but that doesn't mean I'm growing desperate.

title: For Sale:  Sporting equipment in Avon **avoid**
postcontent:
To the ad regarding sporting equipment in Avon 
Claiming ammo in stock
This is clearly the owner posting this ad to lure in customers
He had very little ammo in stock
Looking to get $75 for the last brick of .22 he had
Also looking to get $30 for a 225 pack of golden bullets
He claimed he had to buy the brick for $65 an was only going to make $10
It's people like this who are perpetuating this firearms crisis
And I use the term crisis because frankly paying more
Then $20 for a brick of .22 is a insult to the very culture we are trying to maintain
Furthermore hearing this guy use the undereducated politicians to
Line his own pockets was adding insult to injury
People like this wonder why they have no business when they are
Charging 499 for a basic mossberg 500
 Sorry for going on a rant but I wanted to let all of my friends here in armslist know
Before you drive 30 miles out of the way due to false advertising
